Editor’s Notes / 93 



Rosa Luxemburg was born in Poland in 1871. She was an 
active socialist from an early age, representing the Polish Social 
Democratic Party at the Congress of the Second International when 
only 22. Most of her life was spent in Germany, where she wrote for 
— and sometimes edited — socialist publications, making many 
important theoretical contributions to the debates within the German 
Social Democratic Party. On the outbreak of the First World War in 
1914, she was among the few members of the SPD who refused to 
support the war. Released from prison in November 1918, she threw 
all her energy into the revolution that followed Germany’s defeat. 
She was murdered by reactionary troops in January 1919. 

Tony Cliff is a member of the Socialist Workers Party in 
Britain. His many books include Rosa Luxemburg, a political 
biography written in 1959 and re-published by Bookmarks in 1980. 



