1. References throughout are to the Russian Revolution of 1905. 
Rosa Luxemburg wrote The Mass Strike in the summer of 
1906. 

2. The German Social Democratic Party (spd) was at the time the 
world’s largest socialist party, claiming nearly a million members 
and publishing scores of papers every day. It had a massive 
bureaucracy of full-time officials, both political and trade union, 
and was prone to see a divide between poltical and economic 
struggle. Rosa Luxemburg spent most of her life in Germany in 
exile from her native Poland, and she became a leading member 
of the revolutionary tendency inside the spd. The Mass Strike 
was written partly as a contribution to debates inside the party, 
as its full title. The Mass Strike, the Political Party and the 
Trade Unions, shows. 

3. The ‘lumpenproletariat’ is what Marx calls ‘the stagnant ele- 
ment’, those permanently excluded from the process of produc- 
tion (in distinction to the proletariat, the working class), among 
whom he includes ‘vagabonds, criminals, prostitutes ... the 
demoralised, the ragged . . .’ 

4. The International Workingmen’s Association, or ‘First Inter- 
national’, which was set up by Marx and Engels in 1864. 

5 . Eduard Bernstein and Kurt Eisner, two leading members of the 
German spd. 

6. Kladderadatsch means a great noise, or hubbub. 

7. The Russian national assembly. 

8. At the Congress of the SPD in autumn 1905 at Jena there was a 
debate about whether the party should at any time consider 
calling for a mass strike by workers. The ‘Jena resolution’, 
which was passed, approved the calling of a general strike — but 
only if the government attempted to restrict the right to vote. 

9. At the German Trade Union Congress, which followed the Jena 
Congress, even a theoretical discussion of the general strike 
tactic was labelled as ‘playing with fire’ and banned. Thus the 



